Palantir Vision interviewed you about Palantir's stock architecture. After listening to the video, I posted the following comment. (No reply yet.) Please tell me what you think.

If Palantir F shares are not diluted as more regular shares are issued Tiel, Karp, and other class F owners won't care about dilution. Their only concern will be to keep the standard share price high enough so that they can continue to issue shares that the public will buy. The risk for them is that once the market catches on to this game, the share price will collapse. Who would want to buy $PLTR stock if management's strategy is to use the stock as a piggy bank for their own needs? Also, if employees are being paid with regular stock, they won't be very happy about being used like this.

With a stock going to 500, entry price of 35 or 65 makes a huge difference.  If I have $1000 to buy a stock, buying at $35 means that I will have $14,285.   if I buy at $65, that means I will have $7592.  (Assuming that I can buy fractional shares also for my few left over dollars.)  Well, that's a different of $14,285 vs $7592 which is $6592.  That's ALMOST double a difference. So the difference stays the same in terms of percentage, which magnifies the difference over time in absolute dollars. This is why I don't understand those who say the entry price is not that important if a stock is going to give big gains.

If you like Deutsche B√∂rse, you have to look elsewhere for the real returns. There is a paradigm shift happening in Germany right now when it comes to buying stocks. A lot of new Brokers like Trade Republic are popping up everywhere and are gaining customers like crazy. None of these brokers process their trades using Xetra (Deutsche B√∂rse), but instead they rely on the exchanges of Lang & Schwarz, Baader Bank and Tradegate. The profits of those companies are exploding like crazy. Lang & Schwarz for example generated almost 10‚Ç¨ of EPS just in Q1 2021. Earnings for all of 2021 were 12‚Ç¨. The stock price sits just below 120‚Ç¨ right now, so they are insanely cheap for their current earnings. The market is distrusting their future ability to generate high earnings right now, but with Inflation looming in Europe and no interest for depositors at banks, Germans are slowly but surely waking up and start investing their money into stocks. Because of that I don't really see that trend stopping any time soon.

The same applies to Baader Bank, btw. Those companies are small, institutions haven't picked it up yet. I've been holding since 28‚Ç¨ and I'm not even thinking about selling a single share. The best is yet to come. Lang & Schwarz has a forward PE ratio of just 5 with potentially more growth ahead. This sounds like a perfect Sven Investment ;)

Thanks Sven, nice video. On Wednesday of this week David Swensen of Yale University died of cancer aged 67. Swenson was considered the father of modern portfolio/fund management. He was creator of the Yale Model. He managed a 12.8% annual return for over 30 years.

Want to know why your pension or mutual acts the way they do - it‚Äôs probably due to him. I recommend reading his two most popular books, Pioneering Portfolio Management and Unconventional Success (more geared towards individual investors). They will explain to you how to set up a portfolio. The first book is considered almost the bible of fund managers.

You might think you can do better with your money, than a fund. But without arming yourself with the basics you might not. No such thing as too much knowledge, as long as it does not become doctrine. I recommend both books

I completely disagree. 
A few months ago I had a very detailed look at the 'IOO' ETF (100 big companies in the world). 
For all of those 100 companies I calculated their 'intrinsic values' for a 10% return, similar to what Sven does and I was actually shocked by what I found.  
First of all a large proportion of the ETF was made up by a few very overvalued big US tech companies (Apple, Microsoft, etc.). In fact the more overvalued those companies are, the more the ETF will have to buy them, so you end up with even more........ 
Secondly most of the very large European companies that Sven just described in his video are part of the ETF as well. Typically they have wildly fluctuating earnings, sometimes even constantly dropping earnings, but very high valuations, so to me they are very undesirable. 
All in all my conclusion was that a $100 investment in the ETF only gave me an 'intrinsic value' of $60, so I concluded it was a very poor investment. 
I therefore completely agree with Sven. Pick individual companies with good earnings history, strong earnings growth potential and good fundamentals, but be patient and only buy those that  happen to be cheap.

@Jan Ligthart Chinese immigrant here, top of my class and currently working in a STEM field.
I have no words to describe how ridiculously lazy kids in the West are right now. They're more concerned about social media than they are about studying.
Kids often skip class and disrespect their teachers. They threw paper at me because I would raise my hand and give the right answer. Even in grade 12 calculus, some kids couldn't even graph a parabola, so about 25% of the class dropped out within a week. This is the current state of schooling in the West.
One more thing I find insane in the West is the debate between "rote learning" and "discovery based learning"
It's a stupid question because if you spend the time, you can have both. But if you don't put in the time, then you will have neither.
It's like asking "should I cook the main course or should I cook desert?". The right answer is that you can have both, if you spend enough time in the kitchen.
America is incredibly reliant on immigrants, many of them East Asian. Look at the engineering department at any university and you'll see what I mean.

The West has a legacy of scientific innovation, a result of the historical "great divergence". China missed out on 400 years of scientific progress.
The starting point for China was insanely low, as China had a mostly illiterate population living in a country that had few roads, plumbing or running water. Then they‚Äôre hit with Mao‚Äôs insane experiments, and the list goes on.
What I‚Äôm saying is they needed at least a couple of decades of reconstruction and schooling to even come close to being able to make well-designed products able to compete on the international stage. You have to start somewhere, right?
So if Mao died in 1976, then don‚Äôt you think it‚Äôs reasonable to give these Chinese kids 30 years to study their math before making judgements on the effectiveness of their studying methods?
East Asians study for hours upon hours, and we soak up the material that nobody else wants to learn because they're too busy smoking weed or skipping class.

Some people say East Asian studying methods don't work.
But my question is "What about me? I'm a Chinese immigrant who grew up here. Do I have good studying methods? Do I have creativity?"
If you say no, then why was I at the top of my class? Why am I successful in the workplace?
If you say yes, then you'll be sad to hear that kids in East Asia study in much the same way. I have relatives living in China, trust me I know.

@Nemutai666 our top line machines (EUV, EXE) absolutly have no competition. Older models have competitors like Nikon, Canon who can make the same "size" chips to keep it simple. But they cannot assure the same serviceability, cleanliness (contamination of the chips is a big problem for the process), output,... Therefore we currently have about 86% market share. And the moat is big due to the complexity of the machine. I hope that answers your question.

@tommy lasatira Thats what everybody has been saying for the last decades as well but we keep meeting the Moore's law. Well i should say the architects at our company which are the brains behind it. Which basically means every 2 years we double the amount of transistors per mm2. We know the average atom size is 0.1-0.5 nm and our top line model coming up will when finetuned Probably  be able to write 2-3nm lines. That still gives room to improve. But indeed a good point, if we reach that point the machine with the highest serviceabiity, uptime, cleanliness (contamination is a big issue and ruins the process),.. etc will be market leader. Currently no other company is even coming close to what we can deliver and thus we have 85% market share. We do have older generation models which can do 7nm. Competitors like nikon or canon can do that to but they are behind on the other important metrics i mentioned before. I hope that answers your question.

@crimiss1 The IBM 2nm process is still a lab project. So is TSMC's 1nm process. They are all not yet production-worthy. No process tool from OEM are developed. I would venture to guess that the 1nm and 2nm process will not be in production for another 4-6 years from today. We can check back on that time.

@Hermit Ally The barrier is technical one. ASML is a system integrator of 5000+suppliers. Some of these are unique in the whole wild world: It laser source, its optics, its ultrapure tin source....too many to be listed here. It is not the problem that can be solved by just piling up money. Otherwise, the Chinese would have done it. The success of ASML's EUV tool is a technical compilation from 1990's by working closely with EUV project spearheaded by Intel, and later on with the collaboration by TSMC in the 193 immersion Litho project. All these are not easily duplicated.

@Tom Nash If you look at the suppliers of ASML, it is about a list of 5000 from all over the world. Since the technical challenge is immense, the barrier to entry is so high, there is currently only two or three other competitors of the similar (and less capable) players exist. None of them care capable of producing EUV tools. Since there is no alternative, and within a few years, there is no hope of having any competent competitors are able to appear, I doubt any government of the world will be wise to wield anti trust stick on this one. So, the real competition comes from ASML's  (and its 5000 suppliers) inability to produce enough parts and tools to meet the market demands. In other words, if I can use a typical phase used when talking about TSLA products, "it is not a demand problem, it is a supply problem". Only thing prevented ASML stock to the moon, is the lack of production capacity. I see the situation will last for another 2-3 years.
